zed": true, "mention": "AR", "obj": "gene", "prob": null, "span": {"begin": 542, "end": 544}}, {"id": ["CUI-less"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "cytoplasm", "obj": "cell_type", "prob": 0.5111700296401978, "span": {"begin": 560, "end": 569}}, {"id": ["mesh:D000728"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "androgen", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.9981226325035095, "span": {"begin": 731, "end": 739}}, {"id": ["CUI-less"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "-response elements", "obj": "DNA", "prob": 0.7519280910491943, "span": {"begin": 739, "end": 757}}, {"id": ["CUI-less"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "target gene", "obj": "DNA", "prob": 0.570938766002655, "span": {"begin": 772, "end": 783}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:367", "231", "2232"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "AR", "obj": "gene", "prob": null, "span": {"begin": 844, "end": 846}}, {"id": ["CUI-less"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "cytoplasm", "obj": "cell_type", "prob": 0.5745171904563904, "span": {"begin": 966, "end": 975}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:367", "231", "2232"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "AR", "obj": "gene", "prob": null, "span": {"begin": 987, "end": 989}}], "text": "The androgen receptor (AR) belongs to the steroid hormone receptor family and mediates the biological effects of androgens. Increased AR activation described in this KE is occurring in complex biological systems such as tissues and organs in vivo due either to AR agonism (i.e. activation of the receptor by a compound) or to increased levels of the endogenous hormones testosterone or dihydrotestosterone (DHT). It is thus considered distinct from KEs describing either AR agonism or increased hormone levels.  In the absence of ligand, the AR resides in the cytoplasm. Upon binding of endogenous hormone or a compound acting as an agonist, the receptor is activated, forms a homodimer, translocates into the nucleus and binds to androgen-response elements and regulates target gene transcription by recruiting cofactor protein complexes. The AR can also exert rapid non-genomic action by binding to plasma membrane proteins and activating kinase signalling in the cytoplasm. Increased AR activity can have various effects in vivo, including on sexual development and reproductive function, as well as effects on other organs such as adipose tissue, bone, brain, cardiovascular system, hair, muscle and skin (Dalton et al., 2010; Davey &amp; Grossmann, 2016; Luetjens et al., 2012; Naamneh Elzenaty et al., 2022; Sutinen et al., 2017).", "timestamp": "Fri May 15 22:01:06 +0000 2026"}